This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

1:28 PM Defendant Theresa Huberta Swanson appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Michael Charles Hoffman appeared by video for Theresa Huberta Swanson.  Attorney Angela M Wilson in court for State of Wisconsin. Court calls cases 22CF39 and 22CF226. Attorney Hoffman verifies address. Attorney/Defendant acknowledges receipt of the complaint in 22CF226, waives a formal reading, enters pleas of not guilty to the misdemeanor count(s), and requests a preliminary hearing. 

In 22CF39, Attorney/Defendant acknowledges receipt of the motion for bail modification. State indicates that due to defendant's recent behavior a more specific bail condition of giving DHHS an hour notice is appropriate. Court recites new proposed conditions to defendant. Defendant objects to the new proposed condition. State indicates that the new condition is necessary for protection of victims and preservation of defendant's right to see her children. Court notes concerns over limiting defendant's access to public offices in the government center. State indicates that they are in receipt of text messages from defendant that reference mass shootings. With current behavior and text messages, Sate feels that the new condition is necessary. Court indicates that the condition needs to be tailored to protection of the victims, such as notifying Human Services an hour advance notice prior to arriving at the office. Defendant objects to a bail condition. Court amends bail condition to include notifying Human Services by phone call an hour in advance to arriving at the office.

In 22CF226, State asks for $1,000 cash. No contact with DH except through Health and Human Services. Recites FTAs and cites defendant's behavior. Attorney Hoffman indicates that defendant has lived in the area for her entire life, family in the area, and significant ties to community, and notes that defendant has appeared at most of her hearings. Can not post any money towards bail. Asks court for signature bond. Court notes concerns over failure to follow court orders/instructions, defendant's behavior, and charges alleged. Court orders $1,000 cash. No contact with DH except through Health and Human Services. Court addresses the defendant, clarifies no contact condition and indicates that continued behavior may warrant up to $10,000 cash bail.
